 Solution:
The spherical coordinates $(\rho, \theta, \phi)$ of a point correspond to the rectangular coordinates $(x, y, z)$ as follows:

\begin{align*}
x &= \rho \sin\phi \cos\theta,\\
y &= \rho \sin\phi \sin\theta,\\
z &= \rho \cos\phi.
\end{align*}

The point with spherical coordinates $(\rho, \theta, -\phi)$ corresponds to the point with rectangular coordinates

\begin{align*}
x &= \rho \sin(-\phi) \cos\theta = -\rho \sin\phi \cos\theta,\\
y &= \rho \sin(-\phi) \sin\theta = -\rho \sin\phi \sin\theta,\\
z &= \rho \cos(-\phi) = \rho \cos\phi.
\end{align*}

Since $\sin(-\phi)=-\sin\phi$ and $\cos(-\phi)=\cos\phi$, the rectangular coordinates of the point are

\begin{align*}
x &= -\rho \sin\phi \cos\theta,\\
y &= -\rho \sin\phi \sin\theta,\\
z &= \rho \cos\phi.
\end{align*}

We can express $x$, $y$, and $z$ in terms of the original coordinates $(-5, -7, 4)$:

\begin{align*}
x &= -\rho \sin\phi \cos\theta = -\rho \sin\phi \cos(\theta + \pi) = -\rho \sin\phi \cos\theta,\\
y &= -\rho \sin\phi \sin\theta = -\rho \sin\phi \sin(\theta + \pi) = -\rho \sin\phi \sin\theta,\\
z &= \rho \cos\phi = \rho \cos(\phi + \pi) = -\rho \cos\phi.
\end{align*}

Comparing with the original coordinates, we have $\rho = 4$, $\sin\phi = -\frac{7}{4}$, $\cos\theta = -\frac{5}{4}$, and $\cos\phi = -\frac{4}{4} = -1$.

